  "name": "Veterinary Medical Record Analysis",
  "summary": "This skill guides the production of an attorney-grade analysis of veterinary medical records for animal cruelty, neglect, and veterinary malpractice matters. It provides a structured forensic methodology encompassing record authentication and inventory, granular timeline reconstruction, disciplined extraction of objective clinical data, identification of standard-of-care decision points, detection of record integrity issues, and development of targeted expert questions. The workflow emphasizes the critical separation of documented fact from medical inference and expert opinion, incorporates adversarial awareness and anti-hallucination safeguards for legal and medical citations, and requires attorney supervision before any use of the work product.",
  "content": "# Veterinary Medical Record Analysis for Cruelty Cases and Malpractice Claims\n\n## 1. Opening Context\n\nThis skill produces an attorney-grade, litigation-ready analysis of veterinary medical records that extracts objective medical facts, reconstructs a clinically coherent timeline, and identifies potential indicators of animal cruelty or neglect, or potential veterinary malpractice. In cruelty matters, the work product must translate clinical observations\u2014body condition score, dehydration status, wound chronicity, parasite burden, pain assessment\u2014into legally relevant proof of suffering, duration, and causation while preserving the chain between what the record shows and what a factfinder may infer. In malpractice matters, the analysis must isolate what was done, when, and why, then evaluate whether documented care plausibly satisfied the applicable standard of care and whether deviations can be tied to patient harm.\n\nUnlike human medical records, which are highly standardized under HIPAA and federal regulations, veterinary records vary significantly in quality, terminology, and detail depending on the practice type (general practice versus specialty or emergency), the software platform used (e.g., Cornerstone, AVImark, eVetPractice), and the jurisdiction's regulatory oversight. Competent execution therefore requires more than summarizing notes; it demands a forensic approach to identifying gaps in care, deviations from established protocols, and physiological markers of neglect or trauma. When done poorly, record analysis becomes advocacy masquerading as fact, or worse, an inaccurate medical narrative that collapses under cross-examination. Common failures include conflating diagnoses with differentials, overstating certainty, missing confounders (preexisting disease, owner noncompliance, financial constraints), or citing \"standards of care\" without identifying the competent comparator and applicable professional guidance. High-quality execution is faithful to the record, careful about medical inference, explicit about uncertainty, and structured so that a prosecutor, civil litigator, expert witness, or investigator can rely on it as a roadmap for charging decisions, expert retention, discovery, deposition preparation, and trial presentation.\n\n## 2. Understanding the Context and Purpose\n\nVeterinary records are hybrid documents: they contain clinical observations, diagnostic reasoning, treatment decisions, client communications, and billing artifacts. The strategic purpose of the analysis depends on the nature of the matter.\n\nIn animal cruelty and neglect cases, the records often become the most contemporaneous and neutral evidence of the animal's condition and suffering, especially where lay witnesses are conflicted or unsophisticated. The analysis focuses on the absence of care or the duration of suffering. The record is used to establish a timeline of how long an injury or condition\u2014emaciation, untreated infection, fracture\u2014persisted before intervention. For the prosecutor or animal control agency, the analysis maps clinical findings to statutory elements: harm, pain or suffering, duration, the caretaker's intent or knowledge or recklessness, and causation. The goal is not to \"prove cruelty\" directly but to extract the objective clinical data that supports those elements while identifying alternative explanations the defense will raise. A strong analysis uses disciplined attribution language: \"recorded as,\" \"noted by,\" \"measured,\" \"documented impression,\" and \"differential,\" rather than conclusory assertions.\n\nIn veterinary malpractice claims, the analysis focuses on the quality of care. The attorney must determine whether the veterinarian's actions fell below the standard of care\u2014the level of skill and diligence that a reasonably prudent veterinarian would exercise under similar circumstances. This involves scrutinizing diagnostic choices, surgical techniques, anesthetic protocols, and post-operative monitoring. The record analysis serves as the foundation for determining what the veterinarian knew or should have known, what options were discussed, what informed consent was obtained, whether monitoring and follow-up were adequate, and whether complications were recognized and managed in a timely manner. It also helps assess causation and damages, including additional veterinary bills, death or euthanasia costs, and any emotional distress or diminished value claims where permitted by the jurisdiction. Because veterinary malpractice is typically governed by state tort law and professional negligence principles, the standard of care is usually established through expert testimony. The analysis should therefore be organized to facilitate expert review: define the clinical issues, isolate decision points, and identify missing documentation or departures from routine practice that an expert will scrutinize.\n\nThis work product may be read by multiple audiences with different expectations: investigators want a clean timeline and red flags; prosecutors want elements support and defensibility; civil litigators want breach, causation, and damages framing; experts want clinically precise data; and courts want reliability, transparency, and the separation of fact from opinion. The analysis must remain within the LLM's proper role: it can organize, summarize, and flag issues, but any medical conclusions, diagnoses, and standard-of-care opinions should be presented as hypotheses requiring qualified expert confirmation.\n\n## 3. Prerequisites and Information Gathering\n\nBefore writing any substantive analysis, obtain the complete record universe and understand what is missing. The LLM should ask the user for any absent core materials and should not fill gaps with assumptions.\n\nAt minimum, collect the complete patient file (the \"chart\"), including all SOAP notes (Subjective, Objective, Assessment, Plan), intake and history forms, physical exam notes, nursing and technician notes, progress notes, anesthetic and surgical records if any, medication administration logs, discharge instructions, follow-up communications, and euthanasia records if applicable. Also collect all diagnostic reports: laboratory panels (CBC, chemistry, urinalysis), fecal tests, cytology and histopathology, imaging reports (radiography, ultrasound, CT, MRI), toxicology, necropsy reports, and any consultant or specialist reports. Note that raw diagnostic images (such as DICOM files for radiology) may be needed for independent expert review, but the written reports are essential for the initial analysis.\n\nIn cruelty matters, also request animal control intake forms, shelter medical records, photographs (including body condition images and lesion documentation), seizure logs, chain-of-custody documentation for samples and specimens, and any forensic veterinary reports. The intake notes from the first responding veterinarian or shelter are often the most critical evidence of the animal's baseline condition upon seizure.\n\nBilling and accounting records are not \"medical\" in the strict sense, but they are often crucial for timeline verification and reasonableness assessment. Request invoices, itemized charges, treatment plans and estimates, deposit and refund records, and notes regarding declined diagnostics or \"client refused\" entries. Invoices are frequently the most accurate way to verify which services were actually performed versus those merely recommended. In malpractice matters, request communications that bear on informed consent: signed consent forms, risk disclosures, cost estimates, and documented phone calls.\n\nGather contextual facts that will govern interpretation: species, breed, age, sex, reproductive status, weight (and weight trend if available), ownership history, husbandry and diet and housing conditions, vaccination and preventive care history, prior medical conditions, prior injuries, and any third-party interventions. Ask the user for the governing jurisdiction and case posture (criminal investigation versus filed charge; civil pre-suit versus active litigation), because that affects evidentiary framing, discovery needs, and confidentiality constraints.\n\nA critical note on software systems: many veterinary practices use electronic medical record platforms such as Cornerstone, AVImark, or cloud-based systems. If you do not have the complete unabridged digital record\u2014including internal communication logs, audit trails, and metadata\u2014the analysis may be incomplete. The user should confirm that they have requested the full digital export, not merely a printed summary, which may omit communications, declined-service notations, and edit histories.\n\nIf any of the above categories are missing, the LLM should pause and ask targeted follow-up questions. For example: \"Do you have the anesthetic monitoring sheet and medication administration record for the procedure on the specified date? If not, do you have a subpoena response indicating it does not exist?\" This is a core anti-hallucination guardrail: the analysis must distinguish \"not documented\" from \"did not occur.\"\n\n## 4. Step-by-Step Process\n\n### Step 1: Authenticate, Inventory, and Preserve the Record Set\n\nBegin by treating the record set as potential evidence. The first job is not medical interpretation but evidentiary hygiene: identify what providers and facilities generated records, what date ranges are covered, and whether the production appears complete. Note whether the records are originals, certified copies, screenshots from practice management software, or summaries. Where possible, capture metadata: file names, timestamps, page counts, and any certification or attestation language.\n\nCreate a document inventory narrative that a lawyer can later convert into an exhibit list. Describe the sources and their relationship. For example: \"Records reviewed include: (i) 'Clinic A SOAP notes' dated 2024-01-03 through 2024-02-11 (16 pages, EMR export); (ii) CBC/Chemistry/UA from Reference Lab collected 2024-01-03 at 14:22, reported 2024-01-03 at 19:10; (iii) Radiology report for right forelimb study dated 2024-01-04; (iv) Invoices numbered 1120 through 1142 with itemized charges and 'client declined' notations.\"\n\nIn cruelty matters, explicitly track chain-of-custody touchpoints for physical evidence (blood, urine, tissues) and photographs: who collected it, when, where it was stored, who transported it, and to whom it was released. Even documenting incompleteness is valuable\u2014it frames subpoena follow-up and can become significant at trial.\n\nCommon mistakes include assuming the record is complete because it appears lengthy, ignoring billing artifacts that reveal undocumented services, or failing to note absent components such as missing anesthesia logs or monitoring sheets. Opposing counsel will exploit these gaps to argue spoliation or poor documentation in malpractice matters, or to attack reliability and chain-of-custody in cruelty matters. The analysis should highlight missing record categories without accusing anyone of wrongdoing. The user should consult local evidentiary rules for business-records authentication, certification, and subpoena practice, which vary by jurisdiction.\n\n### Step 2: Build a Granular Timeline Separating Observation, Inference, and Action\n\nReconstruct a timeline with enough granularity to support legal elements and causation analysis. Legal outcomes often hinge on when a symptom was first noted and when action was taken. In a malpractice case, a delay of four hours in diagnosing a gastric dilatation-volvulus can be the difference between life and death. In a cruelty case, the timeline demonstrates the duration of neglect.\n\nVeterinary records often contain internal inconsistencies: a history section may say \"vomiting for three days\" while the triage note says \"vomiting for one week.\" Place each entry into one of three categories: (1) observed or measured findings (temperature, weight, body condition score, capillary refill time, lesion dimensions, lab values); (2) reported history (client statements, third-party observations); and (3) clinician inference or assessment (problem list, differential diagnoses, clinical impression). Then add actions taken (medications, procedures, referrals, recheck instructions). For each entry, identify the provider who made it.\n\nCross-reference the SOAP plan with the invoice to verify whether recommended diagnostics were performed or declined. A \"client declined\" notation is a common finding that cuts both ways: in malpractice defense, it shows the veterinarian made the correct recommendation; in cruelty prosecution, it may demonstrate an unwillingness to provide necessary care.\n\nTimestamp entries when possible and acknowledge uncertainty when timestamps are absent. If the chart lacks times, use dates and sequence markers (\"same visit,\" \"later that day,\" \"next-day recheck\"). For hospitalization, separate admission, daily rounds, significant events, and discharge. In cruelty matters, integrate non-veterinary events (seizure date, shelter intake, transport) alongside veterinary entries, making clear which events come from which source.\n\nThe following illustrative timeline entry demonstrates evidentiary discipline: \"2024-03-02: Intake history documents owner report of reduced appetite 'for about two weeks.' Physical exam documents BCS 2/9, tacky mucous membranes, and fleas noted. Clinician assessment lists 'dehydration' and 'possible GI disease' as problems. Plan includes SQ fluids and fecal testing; invoice reflects fecal test performed. (Source: Clinic A SOAP note; Invoice #1182.)\"\n\nCommon mistakes include collapsing everything into a single narrative (\"The dog was neglected for months\") without anchoring to recorded findings, or treating a clinician's differential diagnosis as a confirmed diagnosis. Opposing counsel will attack overreach by highlighting alternative causes and ambiguities. A robust timeline will explicitly note competing temporal indicators and flag the need for expert input on chronicity. Also be alert for phone calls and \"curbside\" conversations documented in the record. Often an owner calls a clinic multiple times before scheduling an appointment; these calls establish notice of the animal's deteriorating health.\n\n### Step 3: Extract Objective Clinical Data and Normalize It for Legal Use\n\nAfter the timeline, perform disciplined data extraction. The goal is to create a factual substrate: vitals (temperature, pulse, respiration), body condition scores, pain scores, lab values, imaging findings, medications (dose, route, frequency), procedures, and documented responses to treatment. Normalize units (kilograms versus pounds; Celsius versus Fahrenheit), convert where necessary, and retain the original recorded value alongside any conversion. Record reference ranges exactly as provided by the lab report; do not substitute generic ranges, as these can vary slightly by laboratory (IDEXX versus Antech, for instance).\n\nFor cruelty matters, prioritize data that supports elements of suffering and duration: body condition score (typically on a 1-to-9 scale, where 1 is emaciated and 5 is ideal), weight trend over serial visits, hydration status, parasite load, skin condition, dental disease scoring, pressure sores, fecal or urine scalding, wound infection or necrosis, fractures (especially healing stages that suggest chronicity), and behavioral notes consistent with pain or fear. For suspected poisoning, extract toxin testing, coagulation results, neurologic findings, and time-to-treatment. For trauma, extract lesion locations, dimensions, and imaging descriptions.\n\nFor malpractice matters, prioritize data relevant to diagnosis and monitoring: pre-operative labwork and ASA status (if recorded), anesthetic protocol and monitoring parameters (blood pressure, heart rate, oxygen saturation, capnography), fluid rates, analgesia, antibiotic timing, imaging interpretation, recheck instructions, and deviations from expected post-procedure course. Also extract \"client declined\" diagnostics and financial discussions because they can be central to comparative fault or assumption-of-risk narratives.\n\nPresent extracted data in prose rather than raw tables, maintaining attribution. For example: \"The record documents weight 18.2 kg on 2024-04-01 and 16.9 kg on 2024-04-15 (loss of 1.3 kg over 14 days; weight trend derived from recorded values). CBC collected 2024-04-01 shows HCT 22% with lab reference range 37\u201355% (as reported by Reference Lab). Imaging impression dated 2024-04-02 notes 'comminuted mid-shaft femoral fracture' and 'periosteal reaction suggesting prior injury' (radiologist impression; chronicity determination requires expert confirmation).\"\n\nCommon mistakes include inventing missing numbers, paraphrasing lab results inaccurately, or ignoring the difference between a lab's machine-generated flag and a clinician's interpretation. Adversarially, opposing counsel may argue that selected data are cherry-picked. Mitigate this by stating the selection logic (\"objective measurements and clinician-recorded findings relevant to nutrition, hydration, trauma, pain, and infection were extracted\") and by noting normal findings that cut against the theory when they are material.\n\n### Step 4: Identify Decision Points and Evaluate Potential Standard-of-Care Issues\n\nThis step differs between cruelty and malpractice matters. In cruelty cases, \"standard of care\" may be relevant insofar as it frames what reasonable caretaking looks like (adequate nutrition, shelter, veterinary attention). In malpractice cases, standard of care is the central axis. In either case, the LLM should not declare that a veterinarian \"breached the standard of care\" as a conclusion. Instead, it should identify decision points, compare documented actions to plausible competent practices, and flag where an expert should be asked to opine.\n\nStart by identifying inflection moments: presentation and triage, diagnostic choices, interpretation of results, treatment initiation, surgical decisions, anesthesia management, discharge timing, follow-up planning, response to deterioration, and referral to specialty or emergency services. For each decision point, articulate what information was available at the time, what the record says was done, and what alternatives were documented (or not documented). If consent or client communications are relevant, quote or closely paraphrase the actual language.\n\nIn malpractice matters, benchmark the veterinarian's actions against professional guidelines. The American Animal Hospital Association (AAHA) publishes practice guidelines on topics including anesthesia and monitoring, dental care, pain management, and life-stage care. The American Veterinary Medical Association (AVMA) publishes practice standards and a Model Veterinary Practice Act. These are not binding regulations in themselves but are widely recognized as expressions of prevailing professional expectations. For example, AAHA Anesthesia and Monitoring Guidelines call for continuous monitoring of blood pressure, heart rate, and oxygen saturation during general anesthesia (see https://www.aaha.org/aaha-guidelines/2020-aaha-anesthesia-and-monitoring-guidelines-for-dogs-and-cats/monitoring/ [VERIFY current URL]). If a surgery log shows only a single blood pressure entry at the start of a sixty-minute procedure, that is a potential deviation worth flagging for expert review. However, it is critical to distinguish \"gold standard\" care from the legally operative \"standard of care.\" A veterinarian is not required to provide the absolute best care available at a university teaching hospital; the standard is the care that a reasonably prudent practitioner in similar circumstances would provide.\n\nIllustrative, appropriately bounded language: \"At initial presentation, the record documents pale mucous membranes and tachycardia. The clinician's assessment lists 'suspect anemia' and plan includes CBC and abdominal imaging. The record does not show a PCV/TS performed prior to discharge; it is unclear whether this was offered and declined or not considered. This is a potential decision point for expert review regarding evaluation of anemia and discharge safety.\"\n\nCommon mistakes include applying human medical standards to veterinary care, ignoring resource constraints common in veterinary practice (particularly in rural settings or general practice versus referral institutions), or failing to consider client refusal and financial limitations. Opposing counsel will emphasize reasonable clinical judgment and inherent variability in veterinary practice, and will argue that adverse outcomes alone do not prove negligence. The analysis should focus on process and documentation: what was assessed, what risks were identified, what monitoring occurred, and whether the plan matched the recorded condition.\n\nJurisdiction-specific considerations are significant here. Some states impose expert affidavit or certificate-of-merit requirements before a malpractice claim can proceed, and specific statutes of limitation or repose may apply. The LLM should ask counsel whether the jurisdiction requires pre-suit expert certification and tailor the analysis to support that requirement. These procedural rules must be verified through web research or attorney confirmation rather than stated from memory.\n\n### Step 5: Translate Clinical Findings into Legally Relevant Indicators of Suffering, Duration, and Causation (Cruelty Focus)\n\nCruelty statutes often turn on neglect (failure to provide food, water, shelter, veterinary care) or affirmative abuse. Veterinary records can support both, but only if the analysis carefully links clinical indicators to the likely time course and impact on the animal.\n\nFor each major clinical problem (emaciation, untreated infection, fractures, parasitism), explain what the record objectively shows and what a qualified veterinarian might infer about duration and suffering, while flagging that those inferences require expert confirmation. Body condition score 1/9 with muscle wasting, persistent parasitism, and pressure sores may be consistent with prolonged inadequate nutrition and husbandry, but differential explanations\u2014chronic disease, malabsorption, neoplasia, geriatric cachexia\u2014must also be noted. Adversarially, the defense will always argue alternative causation.\n\nSearch the records for pain scores (often on a 0\u20134 scale) and for physical descriptions consistent with unaddressed pain: \"guarded abdomen,\" \"vocalizing,\" \"reluctance to move,\" \"self-mutilation.\" Cross-reference these with the medication log. If an animal has a compound fracture and the record shows no administration of opioids or NSAIDs for twenty-four hours, that constitutes documented evidence of unnecessary suffering that a factfinder can understand.\n\nA strong cruelty-focused narrative will also address veterinary attention timing: did the owner seek care promptly after injury or illness onset? Did the record document long-standing symptoms or delayed presentation? Were treatments prescribed that required home compliance, and is there evidence of compliance or noncompliance? \"Client declined\" entries can cut both ways\u2014supporting inability or unwillingness to provide care, but also supporting that veterinary care was sought and options were discussed.\n\nIllustrative balanced causation framing: \"The record documents a flea infestation and dermatitis with excoriations. The clinician notes 'heavy flea burden.' These findings are consistent with prolonged lack of effective parasite prevention; however, the record alone does not establish duration. Expert testimony may address whether the severity described would typically require weeks versus months without treatment.\"\n\nCommon mistakes include treating \"poor condition\" as synonymous with criminal neglect or ignoring medical confounders. The distinction between visible husbandry failures (fecal matting, severely overgrown nails) and less visible internal disease is important for both factual accuracy and jury understanding. Duration estimates should be anchored to what is actually documented: weight trends, serial exams, healing changes on imaging, or necropsy findings.\n\nJurisdiction-specific considerations are critical. Some states define neglect broadly to include failure to provide \"necessary veterinary care to prevent suffering\" (for example, New York Agriculture and Markets Law \u00a7 353 [VERIFY]), while others focus narrowly on food, water, and shelter. Some require proof of a particular mens rea (intent, knowledge, recklessness), while others treat certain categories of neglect as strict or quasi-strict liability offenses [VERIFY]. The analysis should provide an elements-mapping discussion only after counsel supplies the applicable statute or after the LLM performs verified web research with trackable URLs.\n\n### Step 6: Analyze Documentation Quality, Informed Consent, and Causation (Malpractice Focus)\n\nVeterinary malpractice cases frequently rise and fall on documentation and causation. Even where a complication is a known risk, the adequacy of informed consent and follow-up can be dispositive.\n\nBegin by assessing documentation integrity. Is the chart legible, contemporaneous, internally consistent, and reflective of clinical reasoning? Identify missing components that are typically expected for the procedure or condition: anesthesia monitoring sheet, medication administration record, radiograph images versus report only, discharge instructions. Also scrutinize for red flags suggesting record tampering or spoliation. Look for \"late entries\" or notes written days after a patient event. In digital systems, check for timestamps that do not match the event time. Be wary of \"cookie-cutter\" notes where the physical exam findings for a geriatric patient are identical to those of a young healthy animal\u2014this suggests cloning of records, which indicates a lack of actual assessment. If a record appears too complete or lacks any mention of complications that are common for a specific procedure, it may have been sanitized. Request the audit trail or metadata of the electronic medical record system during discovery to determine if entries were deleted or modified after the threat of litigation arose.\n\nNext, focus on informed consent. Determine whether the record shows: diagnosis or working diagnosis communicated to the client; recommended procedures or diagnostics; material risks and alternatives; cost estimates; and client assent. If the record includes a signed consent form, summarize its substance and flag whether it appears generic or procedure-specific. Do not assume what was said off-record; identify only what can be proven from documentation.\n\nCausation requires disciplined chronology. Identify when the alleged deviation occurred and what clinical deterioration followed. Extract post-procedure monitoring details: pain control, vitals, appetite, urination and defecation, incision checks. Note whether the animal was referred or presented elsewhere and what subsequent records show. Where damages are asserted (additional vet bills, death or euthanasia, diminished value), anchor them to the record and invoices. This is the \"but for\" test: but for the alleged deviation, would the outcome have differed? The analysis should present this question for expert determination, not answer it.\n\nIllustrative language supporting expert causation review: \"The record documents that on 2024-06-10 the patient underwent dental extraction under general anesthesia. Post-operative notes document 'slow recovery' and 'pale gums,' with no recorded blood pressure values. The patient re-presented to an emergency hospital on 2024-06-11 with collapse and was diagnosed with severe anemia (ER CBC attached). Expert review is needed to assess whether intraoperative monitoring or post-operative discharge timing contributed to the outcome, and whether earlier intervention would have altered prognosis.\"\n\nCommon mistakes include outcome bias (\"animal died, therefore negligence\") and ignoring intervening causes (owner noncompliance, subsequent trauma, underlying disease). Opposing counsel will highlight that veterinary medicine involves judgment under client constraints and that consent includes known risks. The analysis must fairly present these defenses while identifying the precise points where the record suggests potential departures.\n\nDamages rules vary significantly by jurisdiction. Some states limit recovery to the animal's \"market value\" and exclude emotional distress or sentimental value (see, e.g., the Texas Supreme Court's decision in Strickland v. Medlen, which limited recovery to market value and denied loss-of-companionship damages [VERIFY]). Other jurisdictions allow broader recovery. The analysis should flag damages limitations as an issue for counsel to research in the applicable venue.\n\n### Step 7: Prepare Litigation-Ready Deliverables\n\nConclude by producing three integrated deliverables written in a professional voice.\n\nFirst, a neutral Record Summary that is fact-forward and could be shared with investigators or retained experts. It should start with patient identifiers, record sources, and date range, then present the timeline and key objective findings, carefully attributing each to its source.\n\nSecond, an Issue-Spotting Analysis that distinguishes (a) cruelty and neglect indicators alongside alternative explanations, and/or (b) malpractice decision points, documentation gaps, and likely expert topics. This section should avoid definitive conclusions. It should use calibrated language: \"raises a question whether,\" \"potentially inconsistent with,\" \"requires expert evaluation.\"\n\nThird, an Expert Questions and Follow-Up Requests section that provides targeted prompts for a veterinary forensic expert (cruelty) or veterinary standard-of-care expert (malpractice). These should be anchored to record citations: \"Based on the BCS 2/9 and weight trend between April 1 and April 15, what duration of inadequate nutrition is clinically plausible?\" or \"Given the absence of recorded blood pressure monitoring during anesthesia, what is the expected monitoring practice for this procedure?\" or \"Does the differential diagnosis check explain the weight loss, or is the veterinarian's diagnosis of neglect-related emaciation supported by the available lab work?\"\n\nCommon mistakes include writing a persuasive brief rather than a medical-record analysis, burying the most important decision points, or failing to ask answerable expert questions. Opposing counsel may obtain these analyses in discovery in some contexts; keep tone professional and defensible. The user should clarify whether the analysis is being prepared at counsel's direction for litigation, to support work-product protection arguments, and should label the document accordingly.\n\n## 5. Critical Legal Standards and Compliance\n\nBecause this skill produces material that may influence charging decisions, pleadings, discovery, and expert testimony, it must be executed with professional responsibility guardrails.\n\nCompetence and diligence require that the analysis be accurate, grounded in the records, and explicit about limitations. ABA Model Rule of Professional Conduct 1.1 (Competence) requires that attorneys possess or acquire the legal and scientific knowledge necessary to handle the matter; if the medical record is beyond comprehension, the attorney is ethically obligated to retain a qualified veterinary expert (see Comment 2 to Rule 1.1). ABA Model Rule 1.3 (Diligence) reinforces the obligation to pursue matters thoroughly. An LLM's output must be treated as draft work product requiring attorney review and verification. ABA Model Rule 5.3 (Responsibilities Regarding Nonlawyer Assistance) is particularly relevant: attorneys must ensure that the LLM-generated work product is compatible with their professional obligations.\n\nConfidentiality is central. Veterinary records may include personally identifying client information, payment information, and sensitive communications. ABA Model Rule 1.6 (Confidentiality) requires protection against unauthorized disclosure. The LLM should instruct the user to provide records through secure channels and to redact nonessential personal identifiers when possible while maintaining evidentiary integrity.\n\nCandor and truthfulness matter when the analysis will be used in court filings or presented to investigators. ABA Model Rule 3.3 (Candor Toward the Tribunal) and Rule 4.1 (Truthfulness in Statements to Others) counsel against presenting contested medical inferences as established facts. If the analysis reveals that the client's claims of neglect are medically unfounded\u2014for example, because the animal had a terminal illness causing weight loss despite good care\u2014the attorney must not present false evidence to the court. The work product must clearly separate what the record documents, reasonable inferences that may be drawn, and opinions requiring expert testimony.\n\nExpert witness standards are also relevant. Under Daubert v. Merrell Dow Pharmaceuticals, Inc., 509 U.S. 579 (1993) (or Frye v. United States in jurisdictions that have not adopted Daubert), expert testimony on standard of care must meet reliability and relevance thresholds [VERIFY applicability in specific jurisdiction]. This analysis is a work-product tool to prepare for expert engagement, but the LLM must not be used to replace the expert's affidavit or testimony.\n\nWork-product doctrine considerations apply. This analysis is generally protected under the work-product doctrine if prepared in anticipation of litigation. However, if the analysis is shared with a testifying expert, it may become discoverable under FRCP 26(b)(4) or analogous state rules [VERIFY]. The skill should instruct the user to clarify the intended use and consult counsel regarding discoverability.\n\nPrivilege and confidentiality for veterinary records are nuanced. Veterinary-client privilege exists in some states and not others [VERIFY]. In criminal cruelty investigations, communications with veterinarians may not be privileged. The skill should direct the user to confirm whether a veterinary-client privilege applies in their jurisdiction, how it may be waived, and whether mandatory reporting obligations for veterinarians apply (many states require veterinarians to report suspected animal cruelty [VERIFY]). If the analysis is prepared at counsel's direction, label it \"Attorney Work Product\u2014Prepared at Direction of Counsel\" where appropriate, but do not assume that labeling alone confers protection.\n\nConflicts of interest can arise if the LLM is asked to analyze records for both sides in related matters or to opine on a veterinarian's conduct while also assisting that veterinarian in another matter. ABA Model Rules 1.7 and 1.9 are implicated. The skill should instruct the user to confirm that conflicts checks have been performed.\n\n## 6. Quality Control and Review\n\nQuality control is substantive, not cosmetic. The following review steps must be performed by the supervising attorney before the analysis is used outside the legal team or in any filing.\n\nFirst, verify that every factual assertion is traceable to a record citation (page, date, source). Where the record is ambiguous, the analysis should say so and propose follow-up. Second, confirm that the medical chronology is internally consistent: no events out of order, no mixing of different animals or patients, and no silent leaps from symptoms to diagnoses.\n\nThird, perform a unit consistency check. Ensure that weight (pounds versus kilograms) and lab values (mg/dL versus mmol/L) are consistent throughout the timeline. Miscalculating a dosage by confusing pounds and kilograms is a common source of medical error that can also undermine an analysis.\n\nFourth, perform a differential diagnosis check. Did the treating veterinarian consider other causes? If the veterinarian diagnosed poisoning but the labs show signs of kidney failure from age-related disease, the analysis must flag this discrepancy. Verify that the analysis itself does not adopt a single diagnostic theory without acknowledging alternatives.\n\nFifth, scrutinize legal relevance: does the analysis identify facts that map to the theory of cruelty (suffering, duration, causation, caretaker action or inaction) or malpractice (duty, breach decision points, causation, damages)? A good analysis highlights both the strongest and weakest facts and anticipates defenses.\n\nSixth, ensure that the document maintains the fact-opinion boundary. Any statement that sounds like a conclusion (\"negligent,\" \"abusive,\" \"reckless,\" \"caused\") should be rephrased into supported factual statements plus a qualifier such as \"requires expert determination\" or \"requires legal determination.\"\n\nSeventh, confirm citation integrity. This skill intentionally avoids providing case citations or statutory citations from memory. If the user requests jurisdiction-specific legal standards (elements of cruelty statutes, certificate-of-merit rules, admissibility of business records), the LLM must either perform web research and provide verifiable URLs, or clearly mark the relevant statements as requiring attorney verification. Under no circumstances should the LLM fabricate case names, statutory citations, or guideline URLs. Any reference to professional standards such as AAHA or AVMA guidelines should be verified against the current version applicable to the date of the care at issue, as these guidelines are updated periodically.\n\nFinally, recognize that the output is draft analytical work product and does not constitute legal advice or a formal veterinary forensic report. All medical conclusions must be verified by a qualified Doctor of Veterinary Medicine. The supervising attorney must review for factual accuracy, jurisdictional correctness, privilege strategy, and ethical compliance before the analysis is shared outside the legal team or used in a filing.\n\n## 7. Jurisdiction-Specific Adaptations\n\nThis skill is intentionally jurisdiction-agnostic on substantive criminal and civil elements because cruelty statutes, veterinary-client privilege, professional negligence doctrines, and damages rules vary widely. To adapt the skill, the LLM should ask at the outset for the jurisdiction (state, province, and if applicable, federal versus state court), the cause of action (criminal cruelty, civil cruelty or neglect, veterinary malpractice, consumer protection claim, contract or bailment), and whether any pre-suit procedural requirements apply.\n\nFor cruelty matters, adaptation centers on mapping facts to statutory elements. States differ substantially in how they define \"torture,\" \"cruel neglect,\" \"necessary sustenance,\" and required mental states. Some include veterinary care within the definition of \"necessary care\" while others focus on food, water, and shelter. The analysis should provide an elements-mapping appendix only after counsel supplies the statute or after the LLM performs verified web research with trackable URLs.\n\nFor malpractice matters, adaptation centers on professional negligence rules. Some states impose expert affidavit or certificate-of-merit requirements, specific statutes of limitation and repose, locality rules for defining the standard of care, or caps and limitations on noneconomic damages. In some jurisdictions, recovery for loss of an animal is limited to \"market value\" or \"special value\" (breeding animals, service animals), with emotional distress or loss-of-companionship damages unavailable. The analysis should flag these as issues for counsel and should not state jurisdictional rules without verified sources.\n\nFor cases involving licensed breeders or research facilities at the federal level, veterinary care records should be checked against USDA Animal Welfare Act standards, specifically the regulations at 9 CFR \u00a7 2.40, which establish minimum veterinary care requirements for regulated entities [VERIFY current regulation].\n\nFor privilege, the skill must not assume the existence of a veterinary-client privilege. The LLM should identify whether the records were obtained by consent, subpoena, warrant, or statutory reporting, and instruct counsel to research privilege, confidentiality statutes, and mandatory reporting obligations for veterinarians in the applicable jurisdiction. If the user provides those authorities, the LLM can incorporate them with proper citations and URLs.\n\n---\n\n### Scope Boundary\n\nThis skill covers the extraction and analysis of veterinary medical records for use in cruelty and neglect investigations and veterinary malpractice claims, including timeline reconstruction, objective data extraction, issue spotting, record integrity assessment, and expert-question development. It does not replace: (a) a licensed veterinarian's diagnosis or standard-of-care opinion; (b) a forensic veterinary expert report; (c) legal advice on charging decisions or pleading strategy; or (d) jurisdiction-specific legal research unless the LLM is provided verified authorities or performs web research with trackable URLs.",
